node.text:
Yesterday on #FathersDay, my family celebrated 3 generations of incredible fathers. Husbands who became super dads. Grandfathers who gained a lifeline. And one great grandfather who beams with pride. And I couldn’t feel more blessed this year, to have brought my little man into this world who will one day become a father himself, because he truly has the most amazing role models to look up to. 

Father’s Day is one of the least celebrated holidays in the world. It’s high time we change that and show our appreciation to all the dads who showed up, helped out, learned how, made time, lost sleep, loved soft, played hard, laughed loud, taught right, faced fears, dug deep, stayed true, held on tight, and never gave up. We love you!

node.text:
#SAVEAFGHANISTAN

Today, on August 15 2021, my heart is completely shattered.

While my mother’s country celebrated its Independence Day in India, my father’s country, Afghanistan, has officially fallen… into the hands of Ta|iban rule.

20 years of America’s “War on Terror”. Trillions of tax dollars spent. Countless lives lost. Immeasurable hope for the liberation of the Afghan people, all gone to waste as the US quickly pulled out with no plan for peace and security for the country that it once promised to rebuild. Today, the people of Afghanistan frantically flee for their lives like worthless pawns in a sick game, with no clue what even the following hour will bring. Today, the Afghan diaspora watches 20 years of our hard work for their progress be erased before our very eyes and we cry out for help as the whole world watches, realizing we may never see our fathers’ beloved homeland be stable in our lifetimes.

My shattered heart has been replaced with this stone heart of Lapis Lazuli. One of the world’s most beautiful semi-precious stones, found ONLY in Afghanistan.

I have posted this simple yet powerful image created by @lemaafzal with the hashtag #saveafghanistan in solidarity with its people. Please repost on your pages if you are compelled to do so, just as we did for BLM and so many other humanitarian causes.

God help Afghanistan. 🇦🇫

_______________________

Please see my Afghanistan story highlights for more resources and links to help in this humanitarian crisis.

node.text:
Being a boy mom. Everyone warned me, but somehow I thought I could fight it. “He will steal your heart, mama!” But my heart was already stolen and guarded. By my little girl. I was worried, scared… How could I share my love? She had my entire soul… where would he fit in? They said, ‘don’t worry your heart will grow.’ But how? 

Maybe it was denial. Maybe it was the fear of future guilt. Maybe it was the worry that I would be just like the rest of them, the obsessive mother to a life-time ‘mama’s boy.’ But I didn’t let him in. 

9 months I carried him. Completely different pregnancy compared to my daughter. He was so sweet to me, I could tell even from inside my belly… he was gentle to his mama. But still, my walls were up and I didn’t let him in. 

Then, he was born. That first look took my breath away… Wow. I did not expect this. It was him all along, my little man. A rush of emotion I still can’t describe. God I love him. But, I STILL didn’t let him in. 

We brought him home the very next day. My incision still raw from the day before. But I didn’t want to spend one more minute away from my girl. We did this for her. Now I couldn’t wait to watch her eyes light up as she meets him for the first time. Her forever best friend. And even as I witnessed her hold him with awe and amazement, completely losing her heart to him and finally basking in the new role she’s always dreamt of, I couldn’t let this boy take over my whole heart too, I didn’t want to be ‘that’ mom, and so… I still didn’t let him in. 

But it happened. I don’t know when, I don’t know how. But as much as tried so hard to fight it, somewhere between those million sweet kisses and middle of the night snuggles I found myself so completely lost in him and it just happened. And when I finally realized it, it was too late. I had fallen hard. Just like the rest of them. And you know what? They were right. About everything. And looking back now, 9 months later, I realize he had me all along. I was just too stubborn to admit it. But this girl mom is just CRAZY about her boy. And he is JUST as crazy about me. 🤍🧿
